  {
    "speaker": "interviewee",
    "tag": "RW",
    "text": "And-- right. And it shows a-- a-- a very high number and-- [PAUSES FOR 3 SECONDS] which never was called. These are the stars I wore. And the material itself was very flimsy, so my grandma, Jenny, put in a lining so that it would become sturdy and can be sewn from one garment onto the next. This is a document issued in 1942 by the firm for which my father did forced labor. And this document entitles my father to travel-- travel freely around Berlin to do the necessary work for this particular company. This is a document issued by the Sammellager Grosse Hamburger Strasse-- which, in other words, was a Gestapo prison in Berlin. And it shows that my father, der Jude-- always the word 'Jude' had to appear before any official document, before the name on-- on it. And the I stands for Israel. Before my father was released from the Gestapo prison on February 15, 1943, where he spent approximately seven days to prove with the Aryan papers of my mother that she is an Aryan, and that he should be released. This is a postcard which we received from Theresienstadt. It was dated July 7, 1943. And it informed us that my grandmother, Jenny, had passed away on January 22nd of that year. This is a postcard we received from my uncle, Alfred Lehmann, from Auschwitz-Monowitz. And the card itself is from late 1943, where he tells us that he is healthy, that he has enough food, and that he works, and that he sends us his love. And that's all. The card itself was printed. His signature was his original handwriting. This is a ration card issued for the whole year. As you can see, it has a little-- small fields. And every day in the newspaper, they would announce what you would get for a-- a-- for a specific field. But it also said in the newspaper that all the cards with a J are exempt from the distribution of that particular food. So therefore, we have no stamp in there, and we never got anything on that card. Oh, this is the front of that same ration card. As you can see, it was issued for three people. It means one household got one card-- issued to my father. And we never got anything on the card. This is my ration card, the last one in 1945. It was valid from April 9th to April 29th of '45. As you can see, the word Jude is printed all over the card to clearly identify who the owner is. And on the bottom, it says-- oh, loose coupons are-- are void. So you never were allowed to cut anything off. It had-- had to be done in the store where you bought.",
